title: Motorcycle Helmet Hook for Honda Grom
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
Why buy one, when you can print one?
I wanted a helmet hook for my Honda Grom. I didn't want to pay $15 bucks for one when I could make one for $0.21 cents. But really, who am I kidding? After all my time, this thing cost way more than $0.21 cents...way more than $15. Oh well, I like designing things and it helps others out too, so it's worth it.

Design Notes
The unorthodox design is so that it will print very easily, with little error and so that it will have maximum strength. I am using the 4.25mm version which holds the straps of my helmet. I made a few different sizes in case it needs to hold a buckle or something else that doesn't apply to me specifically. The different measurements indicate how big the gap is in the hook.

Screwed
BTW, if your bar end screw is like mine was, it will seem nearly impossible to remove. If you don't want to strip the Phillps head, I suggest you get the appropriately sized bit, put it in a socket, use a socket wrench and go slow until it breaks loose. I have no idea why that screw had to be in there that tight....was it holding my whole bike together? I just used some thread lock and snuggly tightened it when installing the hook.

Giving Thanks
A lot of time and PLA went into designing this thing. If this design blesses your life in some way, feel free to favor me with a tip as thanks. Gratuities are not required, but are definitely appreciated. Is Thingiverse's tip minimum more than you had in mind? You can tip me any amount that you would like here: https://www.paypal.me/brysonjack
Make sure to include a comment telling me which design it is. Thanks in advance.

Post Script
I have also discovered that it holds my glasses for me while I am putting on my helmet. Bonus!

print_settings.Notes:: At the settings detailed above, I can print a plate of 9 of these in an hour at the cost of 25 cents per plate.  This produces 3 complete fidget widgets in 4 hours at the total cost of $1.  So they end up costing about 33 cents each, about 50% more than the original one-piece design.  Part of that is because they are 10% larger.  Part is because they have more outside edges with solid layers.  But you can decrease the size as well as the number of solid layers if you wish to bring the cost per unit down a few cents. Personally though, the benefits listed below make the extra few cents worth it to me.
print_settings.Printer:: Wanhao Duplicator i3 Plus

description.text:
I have been more hooked on these Fidget Widgets than I ever was any other spinner or top or toy. The fact that they float and can be played with in the pool is just an added bonus! I've been selling and giving these things away faster than I can print them. Alternating the colors on the pieces gives it a really nice effect as they rotate. But adding to that with each piece being two colors really amps it up. I love printing these using the multi-color plugin for OctoPrint so that I can change out the filament and print the pieces in two different colors. But I believe this new "thing" is an improvement over the other models that are out there. I list those reasons further down the page.

I marked this as a work in progress because I'd like to increase tolerances just a bit. It is just a little bit too snug and doesn't rotate in on itself quite as easily as I would like. So a "version 2" might be in the future when I shave off a fraction of a millimeter from the bottom of the piece.

If you print any of these, I'd love to hear how they work out for you and see pictures of them!

Note: I am a big guy with big hands. As such, these fidget widgets are 10% larger than the contributing models. Feel free to scale them back down if you so desire.

UPDATE: A new version of the models was uploaded that have slightly more clearance in the connections so that the completed widget will revolve more freely and silently.

Printer Brand:

Wanhao

Printer:

Wanhao Duplicator i3 Plus

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Doesn't Matter

Resolution:

.3

Infill:

10

Notes:

I print these with light infill so that they will float in the pool and hot tub. The adults like playing with them while they relax and visit with each other! :) And because they are just toys and don't have to be super-high quality, I print them at a .3 resolution for faster printing. The added benefit is that these cheap-to-produce pieces are often the recipient's first introduction to 3D printing and they like to see the print layers. If I was going to make these for a hefty profit, I'd probably decrease the layer height. I also print them with a concentric external fill pattern (a nice option in Simplify 3D) because that produces a nice looking external layer. Because the center surfaces of paired pieces were both against the print bed, you could save yourself a bit of time and plastic by decreasing the solid bottom layers. I just print with four solid layers all the way around though so that they are fairly strong without becoming too heavy. Did I mention I need them to float? ;)

At the settings detailed above, I can print a plate of 9 of these in an hour at the cost of 25 cents per plate. This produces 3 complete fidget widgets in 4 hours at the total cost of $1. So they end up costing about 33 cents each, about 50% more than the original one-piece design. Part of that is because they are 10% larger. Part is because they have more outside edges with solid layers. But you can decrease the size as well as the number of solid layers if you wish to bring the cost per unit down a few cents. Personally though, the benefits listed below make the extra few cents worth it to me.

Why another fidget widget?

There are several reasons why this model is superior (IMO) over preceding models. I'll list them.

  1. Adhesion of original model without sharp corners.
  2. Comfort of rounded "mod" version with less chance of coming away from print bed.
  3. Up to 12 colors in each completed widget.
  4. No requirement for plugins or manual pause in the middle of a print job.
  5. Flexibility of color choices at time of assembly,
  6. Finish is consistent on both side of the piece (no indication of which side was on print surface).
  7. Extra solid layers running down the center of paired up pieces provides extra strength.
  8. These pieces are tiny and are the perfect thing to print with the last coils of filament on a roll. A set of three of these only use 5.8 grams of filament - less than 6.5 feet.
Suggestions

I personally prefer mixing these with 3 each of 4 different colors. But since they are so quick and easy to print (particularly at higher layer heights), I decided to not include a "batch" of 3. But, since I include a single STL in the upload, you can make one if you so desire. Since a full widget would consist of 12 of these units, it is conceivable that you could print a widget with a dozen different colors. Realistically though, printing four different colors of 6 or 9 pieces would give you enough pieces to mix things up color wise in two or three complete fidget widgets. Or you could print 6 each of 2 different colors (ebony and ivory?) and, by carefully alternating them, end up with a nice striped version that produces the same effect that you can get now with alternating solid-color pieces. It's really all up to you.

As another preference, I like for the main center color you see to alternate between light and dark. In order to achieve this, you will need to pair to light halves together and the dark halves together. This is because what you see in the center convergence of the pieces alternates between adjoining pieces and then the other side of those pieces. So, for example, if you were to place white/yellow pieces together and attach them to black/blue pieces, making sure that you assemble them so that the colors on the sets all face the same direction, you would result in the colors turning white, black, yellow, blue, back to white as you rotate them. I mention this because while you can take these apart and re-assemble them, too much of that will wear on the little posts that lock into the holes and you will not end up with a snug fit.

description.text:
An example of 3D model generated with my Gugulele OnShape script…

  • Decorative headless gourd shaped design
  • Soprano ukulele scale length
  • Double rectangular through-body spine
  • Single oval off center sound hole
  • "+|-|+" Bracing
  • Tail-end placement of Planetary tuners
  • 5 pieces using M1.6 socket head screws

I designed this so that friends with "normal" size desktop printer like Makerbot 5th gen that can print about 250mmx200mmx100mm have a shot at trying the project. I have yet to print this particular model so let me know if you have succeeded in printing one.

Third Party Parts:

  • 2x Spine/rods e.g. http://www.acpsales.com/.125-x-.325-Rectangular-Rod.html or https://dragonplate.com/ecart/product.asp?pID=749&cID=20
    • get a 24" long and cut it down to size, can't remember exactly...
    • if you don't use a rod, the neck will bow under string tension
  • Gotoh UPT-UBB-B Tuners e.g. http://www.theukulelesite.com/gotoh-upt-tuner-upgrade.html
    • its possible to use cheaper friction tuners, but need to play with shims and washers like this user http://www.thingiverse.com/make:325819, he uses https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B002HFQ88Y
  • 9x Long Screws (M1.6x10) for fretboard long holes e.g. https://www.amazon.com/M1-6x10mm-Stainless-Socket-Screws-100pcs/dp/B011BNUXNI
    can't remember how many you need, just buy a bag of 100
  • 6x Short Screws (M1.6x4) for short body holes and first fret e.g. https://www.amazon.com/M1-6x4mm-0-35mm-Pitch-Socket-100pcs/dp/B00XP4ZWY2/ just buy a bag of 100
  • You still need to Glue the parts together! The screws are there to provide alignment and help hold parts together while waiting for the glue to cure...

comments.text: The intent is good; execution could be improved by decoupling the smooth rod from the lead screw. With axial and radial loading on a lead screw, there will be resulting harmonics at various speeds. Supporting both ends of the lead screw dampens those harmonics a bit, but leaving the smooth rod coupled definitely results in induced wobble. I haven't done the calculations, but I'm confident the z-axis screws aren't spinning fast enough to induce any significant harmonics. This means the wobble with be exaggerated slightly in the stock x-axis setup. I did see someone make x-axis ends with the decoupling I mentioned; they seemed to work very well to improve print quality. However, if this is really what is wanted, try using a urethane or rubber bushing instead of a bearing. It'll support the end while allowing for extra dampening.

A spinner that costs literally 12 cents + a bearing. Turns out to be cheaper than putting in bearings or steel balls and pennies are readily available.

Put the end caps on and you are ready to roll.

description.text:
A friend of mine was missing a Knob on his Traktor Kontrol X1 and I suggested to him that I could design a replacement and print it on my 3D Printer.

So far it worked out. We'll see how it stands the test of time with heavy use.

If you have comments or improvements, let me know!

Printer:

TronXY X1

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2 mm

Infill:

20%

Notes:

I had to make the bore 0.3 mm wider to fit the shaft because of the dimensional inaccuracy in my printer. I have included the FreeCAD model. Adjust the sizes as you need them.

General Shape

I started out in the Part Design workbench with a Sketch that I planned to revolve. Most of the dimensionally important parts are defined in there. The only important dimension missing from that sketch is the width of the keying part in the bore that registers the part with the shaft and it's keying cut.

For more information, check the FreeCAD file.

Keying Part

To create the Key, I projected the bore circumference into a sketch I mapped to the bottom of the bore. From there, it was a simple construction of a rectangle with the right dimensions.

Stability and Flex

Because the first iteration didnt fit so well, I decided to cut a slot in the bore sleeve. That was done by mapping the important lines into the sketch and constructing a rectangle, which was then pocketed into the part.

The other parts were two connections from the external hull to the bore sleeve, to keep it from breaking off under heavy use. I don't really expect them to be of great importance, but they also don't detract from the other features of the part.

I constructed one of them and then mirrored the feature to the other side of the part.

Chamfers

Top and bottom were chamfered, to get closer to the original look, while maintaining printability.

Grooves for Grip

For this I switched to the Part workbench and made a cylinder in the correct spot and orientation for one of the grooves, and filleted the lower edge to mimic the look of the original part. This will be the tool I use to cut out from the main body.

Then I switched to the Draft workbench where I used the pattern feature (polar) to distribute 16 of the cylinders around the part.

This array I then used as the tool in a boolean cut operation (back in the Part workbench) to cut all the grooves.

Done

I exported the file as an STL and dragged it into Cura to slice it and then I printed it with bright green PLA.

title: Plate with bearing for guiding lead screw

description.text:
ENGLISH VERSION:

Those printed plates are designed for guiding the leads screw from a 3d printer as Prusa i3 Steel. In some shops you can find new structures with new plates for prusas that incorporate this advantage, but with my plates you can do the update without buying any new structure.

This update let that the guidings leads screw are always aligned getting better print quality.

Requirements:
2x printed plates (choose between "bearing" or "blind_bearing")
2x F688zz bearings
4x M3x16 screws
4x M3 nut (you can use the originals)

Assembly:
First remove your screws from your steel plates, then take your printed pieces introduce the bearing (F688zz) under pressure in the printed piece and finally screw it above the steel plates with the news screws.

Others:
You can choose between "bearing" version where you can see the bearings, or "blind_bearing", hiding the bearing and avoiding drop of any dust or dirt inside them.

VERSIÓN EN ESPAÑOL:

Estas piezas impresas han sido diseñadas como guía para los husillos de una Prusa i3 Steel. Podéis encontrar en diversas tiendas nuevos marcos de acero para estas impresoras que incluyen como avance una nueva chapa de tope con taladros donde embutir un rodamiento que asegure que nuestros husillos están siempre alineados. Con mis piezas en 3D puedes ahorrarte este gasto y hacer esta misma actualización sin tener que comprar estas nuevas chapas.

Requerimientos:
2x "chapas" impresas (escoge entre "bearing" o "blind bearing")
2x rodamientos F688zz
4x tornillos de M3x16
4x tuercas de M3 (puedes usar las originales)

Montaje:
Primero retira los tornillos que fijan tus placas de acero, posteriormente ensambla a presión los rodamientos (F688zz) in la placa impresa y finalmente fíjala sobre tu placa de acero con los nuevos tornillos (de mayor dimensión que los viejos para salvar el incremento de anchura).

Otros:
Puedes escoger entre la versión "bearing" que te permite ver el rodamiento o bien la versión "blind_bearing" que lo oculta completamente, evitando que le entre polvo o cualquier suciedad.

This is a easy way to mount two mosfets (one for the hot bed and one for the hot end) to the frame of the anet a6. I designed it by myself and wanted it to look clean and with good cable routing options.

You only need to print 1x the main part and 2x the little clip, which will clamp the upper board.
Only a few screws and nuts are needed. (these were left by my printer build)
Under the lower board is a cutout for the cables of the upper.

The mosfet-mount is attached to the frame by four screws. Two of them are the actual mainboard screws to spare two screws and have enough mounting points.

Features:

  • 4 mounting points to the anet a6 frame
  • clean look and cable routing options
  • very low amount of filament is needed
  • simple assembly, because of inbuild hexagonal holes for the nuts

In addition to the printed parts you need this screws:
4x M3x12 (red marked in the picture, lower mosfet)

description.text:
--- Français ---

Nos imprimantes ne font pas toujours exactement ce qu'on leur demande. Les trous et les cylindres sont rarement exactement aux cotes désirées.

Cette plaque permet de mesurer cet écart pour des trous et des cylindres compris entre 1.0 et 5,9mm de diamètre.

Dans mon cas, les cylindres réalisés sont très proche de la côte souhaitée : 5.21mm réalisé pour 5.2 demandé, tandis que les trous réalisés sont nettement plus petits que souhaités : 5.25mm réalisé pour 5.4 demandé.

--- English ---

Our printers do not always do exactly what they are asked. Holes and cylinders are rarely exactly to the desired dimensions.
This plate allows to measure this deviation for holes and cylinders between 1.0 and 5.9mm in diameter.

In my case, the cylinders made are very close to the desired coastline: 5. 21mm made for 5. 2 requested, while the holes made are much smaller than desired: 5. 25mm made for 5. 4 requested.

Mini-Rocket
==========
  • Sized for a standard (24mm) Estes C11/D engine
  • Separate nose cone with hook for shock-cord and parachute
  • Fins chamfered for spin
  • Fin retainer ring for added stability
  • Large aft surface area provided by fins and retainer ring pull center of pressure behind center of gravity for stability given high-power engine and short length
  • According to Makerware, Total Weight (without engine): 72g
  • According to openrocket approximations:
    • max height: 287m
    • takeoff velocity: 17.2m/s
    • velocity at deployment: 14.9m/s
    • max velocity: 102m/s
    • stability: 0.657cal (anyone who knows what that means, let me know - I couldn't find a clear/succinct answer)
  • Designed not to need supports or rafts, minimizing assembly and printing time/material
  • Thick walls (designed walls, not print shells) are sturdy for continued reuse (working on thinning a little bit to reduce weight and still print simply)

I used the "standard" makerbot 2x settings for ABS: 10% infill, 2 shells, 230C extruders; my only changes were a 115C bed and 80 print speed - It always seems to stick a bit better. No raft and no supports.  
working on a still stable/still easy version with thinner walls. for now it still works and the best part is no raft and no support. The bottom is nice and smooth and I saw no curling, and any unsupported regions are on ≤45° angles so no support is needed (this is a lot easier than clearing out the inside of the tube afterwards)
